### CHAPTER XIV.

1\. The sage asked the spirit of <span id="fr_226"></span>[1](#fn_223.md)
\[wisdom (2) thus: 'Which protection is the more defensive? 3. Which
friend <span id="fr_227"></span>[2](#fn_224) (4.md) and which supporter of
fame are good? 5. Which helper of enjoyment is good? 6. Which wealth is
the pleasanter? 7. And which is the supremest pleasure of all
pleasures <span id="fr_228"></span>[3](#fn_225.md)?'

8\. The spirit of wisdom answered (9) thus: 'The sacred being is the
more defensive protection. 10. A virtuous brother is a good friend. 11.
A child, who is virtuous and an upholder of religion, is a good
supporter of fame. 12. A virtuous wife, who is well-disposed, is a good
helper of enjoyment. 13. That wealth is better and pleasanter which is
collected by honesty, *and one* consumes *and* maintains with duties and
good works. 14. *And* the pleasures which are superior to all pleasures
are health of body, freedom from fear, good repute, *and*
righteousness <span id="fr_229"></span>[4](#fn_226.md).'

